Mice analysis

Jono

Friday 16 Apr 2021

1 Overview

In a certain experiment, the lung weights of two strains of mice were compared. One strain of mice was normal, C57, and the other was a mutant strain, mdx, that develops a condition similar to muscular dystrophy in humans.

The following variables were recorded:

Variable Possible_values
Weight Weight of lungs in mg
Age Age of mouse in weeks. The possible values of age were 3, 6, 12, 26, 39, 52, 65, 78 or 104 weeks.
AgeFactor Week3, Week6, Week12, Week26, Week39, Week52, Week65, Week78 or Week104
Type C57 or mdx

pacman::p_load(tidyverse, tidymodels, MASS, gglm, skimr, gt)

5 Box-Cox analysis

mice_M1 <- lm(Weight ~ Type * Age, data=mice)
mice_bc <- boxcox(mice_M1)

Profile likelihood for Box-Cox transformation of Weight 

bind_cols(
  lambda = mice_bc$x, 
  likelihood = mice_bc$y
  ) %>% 
  filter(likelihood == max(likelihood))

6 Transformation of weight

mice <- 
  mice %>% 
  mutate(
    weight_trans = (Weight^{0.5} - 1) / 0.5
  )

7 Model 2

mice_M2 <- lm(weight_trans ~ Type * Age, data = mice)
anova(mice_M2) %>% broom::tidy() %>% knitr::kable()

8 Model 3

mice_M3 <- lm(weight_trans ~ Type + Age, data = mice)
gglm(mice_M3)

Diagnostic plots for mice_M3 

broom::augment(mice_M3) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(Age, .std.resid)) + 
  geom_point()

Scatterplot of standardised residuals versus age for model mice_M3

9 Model 4

mice_M4 <- lm(weight_trans ~ Type + Age + I(Age^2) + I(Age^3), data=mice)

10 Prediction

new_data <- crossing(
  Age = c(40, 50, 60), 
  Type = c("C57", "mdx")
)
pred <- predict(mice_M4, newdata = new_data, interval = "prediction")
new_data %>% 
  add_column(
    fit = pred[, 1],
    lwr = pred[, 2],
    upr = pred[, 3],
  )
